<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / International Company News: Bertelsmann and Canal Plus agree
to join forces
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL and ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HANOVER, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bertelsmann, the German multimedia group, and Canal Plus, France's leading
pay-TV broadcaster, have agreed to form a joint venture to exploit the
expected proliferation of new television services around the world.
The move is intended to enable both companies to compete more effectively
with the rash of Anglo-Saxon multimedia ventures already established.
Bertelsmann is the largest multimedia group in the world after Time Warner,
and Canal Plus the largest and most profitable pay-TV broadcaster in France.
The deal will extend the co-operation between the two companies, already
partners in the first German pay-TV channel, Premiere, into future
cross-border exercises.
'It will ensure the development opportunities for both our enterprises in an
important future area for the electronic media, including forms of pay-TV,
pay-per-view, video-on-demand, and other special services,' they said.
Bertelsmann pointed out that private television channels - like the
company's highly-successful RTL channel in Germany - were reaching the
limits of financing available from broadcast advertising. New channels would
require new forms of financing.
The advent of digital television would enable the distribution of a new
variety of different channels and services, which would have to be financed
by viewers as they watched or used them.
It said the latest venture was the 'logical international extension' of last
week's agreement between Bertelsmann, Deutsche Telekom and KirchGroup, to
establish a service company to manage and distribute the future pay-TV and
other services on the existing German cable network.
The announcement of the deal comes at a turbulent time for the French group,
which last month became embroiled in a row over the sudden resignation of Mr
Andre Rousselet, its founder and chairman.
</TEXT>
