<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Gecas chief resigns to form new company
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Colm Barrington, president and managing director of GE Capital Aviation
Services, has announced his resignation from the company to form his own
Dublin-based aircraft management company.
Mr Barrington said that he plans to merge his new company 'with a major
international investment company' which will provide the finance for a new
fleet of aircraft, which will then be leased.
He said that he had been considering his move for some time, and had an
agreement with Gecas that he would review his position after four months. Mr
Herb Depp was recently appointed worldwide chief executive of Gecas.
Gecas was set up in November last year as a wholly owned subsidiary of GE
Capital Services, following the restructuring of GPA, the Shannon-based
aircraft leasing company.
GPA had run into serious financial difficulties following its aborted 1992
flotation. Under the restructuring deal, Gecas acquired 44 aircraft from GPA
for Dollars 1.35bn (Pounds 920m), while the remaining 420 aircraft in the
GPA fleet - still owned by GPA - came under Gecas management.
GPA yesterday announced a third-quarter loss of Dollars 18.2m, making total
losses of Dollars 48.6m for the nine months to December 31. The company
reported outstanding debts of Dollars 5.8bn and a net worth of Dollars 195m.
Mr Barrington joined GPA in 1981 and had been a key figure in arranging the
finance for the fleet during its rapid expansion. He also developed GPA's
aircraft securitisation programmes which contributed Dollars 1.5bn in
revenues to GPA. In 1992 he was also appointed GPA's chief operations
officer.
</TEXT>
