<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / UK Company News: BBA sells plastics offshoots for Pounds 25m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBA, the engineering and motor components group, yesterday embarked on the
first stage of a wide-ranging disposal programme with the sale of three
engineering businesses to United Industries, the precision tools and springs
manufacturer.
The move follows the group's decision to focus on four core businesses and
sell up to 12 subsidiaries with a combined turnover of Pounds 200m.
United, in which BBA holds a 21.23 per cent stake, has agreed to pay Pounds
25m cash for Holden Hydroman, Perplas and Railko - all manufacturers of
plastic and polyurethane components.
The Leicester-based group said the acquisitions, funded by a Pounds 26m
placing and open offer, would transform it from a small specialist company
with a market capitalisation of Pounds 6m into an operation worth more than
Pounds 40m.
Mr Tom Brown, United's chief executive, confirmed that BBA would be taking
part in the 1-for-5 offer - involving a total of 186m new ordinary shares at
15p each - to maintain its existing stake.
'This is a mutually beneficial deal to both companies. It allows us to grow
and BBA to refocus,' said Mr Brown.
BBA, which is expected to report annual profits before tax and exceptional
items of about Pounds 54m (Pounds 47.4m) next Monday, also welcomed the
transaction.
Mr Roberto Quarta, chief executive, said the group intended to concentrate
of improving profitability of its automotive, industrial and aviation
operations.
The former BBA companies, which made a combined operating profit of Pounds
2.86m (Pounds 828,000) in 1993, are expected to bolster profits at United,
which admitted that it had been struggling to overcome the effects of
recession.
United incurred a pre-tax loss of Pounds 1.5m on sales of Pounds 19.2m in
the nine months to December 31 last year, against a deficit of Pounds 3.63m
on sales of Pounds 29.6m in the 12 months to April 3.
United warned that it would not be paying a final dividend for the second
successive year.
