<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / Drugs and seeds help Zeneca grow 42%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A solid performance from drugs, seeds and speciality chemicals helped
bioscience group Zeneca post a 42 per cent rise in pre-tax profits for 1993,
at Pounds 627m before exceptional items.
The company's first set of figures since the demerger last summer from ICI
was boosted by currency gains as well as volume growth. Pre-tax profit after
exceptionals was Pounds 642m, in the middle of analysts' expectations.
Sir Denys Henderson, chairman, described the year as 'successful . . .
despite less than ideal trading conditions'.
Trading profit rose to Pounds 713m, a 21 per cent increase. Some 14
percentage points of this increase came from volume growth, 1 percentage
point from increased prices and the balance from currency fluctuations.
Strong cash flow of Pounds 833m, a Pounds 151m increase over 1992, helped
cut year-end net debt sharply from Pounds 391m to Pounds 188m. Gearing fell
from 11.7 to 25.7 per cent.
Earnings per share after exceptional items were 51.7p (10.8p) and the
dividend was confirmed at 27.5p.
The company issued a trading statement on January 21, so there were few
surprises yesterday and Zeneca shares fell 3p to 763p.
Underlying sales growth in the biggest division, pharmaceuticals, was 5 per
cent, rising to Pounds 1.87bn. The top-selling drug, heart treatment
Tenormin, saw sales in constant currency terms fall 22 per cent to Pounds
464m in the face of generic competition.
Mr John Mayo, finance director, said that the rate of Tenormin's decline was
slower than with comparable drugs that had lost patent protection.
However, growth from other products more than made up for the decline in
Tenormin revenues. Sales of the company's second biggest product, Zestril,
another heart treatment, rose to Pounds 416m from Pounds 294m.
By region, The US continued to be easily Zeneca's biggest drugs market with
sales of Pounds 782m (Pounds 661m), but sales in Japan grew more than twice
as fast, from Pounds 190m in 1992 to Pounds 261m last year. France moved
into third place ahead of the UK.
In agrochemicals, trading profit rose just 1 per cent to Pounds 86m on sales
of Pounds 1.47bn. The specialities division saw doubled trading profits of
Pounds 50m on sales of Pounds 1.03bn.
