FT  04 MAR 94 / Observer: Kudlow's high
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Lawrence Kudlow, Bear Stearns' chief economist, who has resigned after eight
years with the company, says he wants to spend more time with his politics.
He's got the experience - General Motors thinks he has broad public appeal,
having long used him as a TV salesman for Cadillac cars.
He's also got the connections, as former deputy budget director in the
Reagan administration and more recently the economic brains behind Christine
Whitman's successful campaign for the governorship of New Jersey.
He turned down Whitman's offer of New Jersey state treasurer, probably
seeking a bigger pool to swim in. Word is he will run for the Republicans
against Daniel Moynihan, the celebrated Democrat senator from New York.
</TEXT>
