<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
American television has, on the whole, managed the race conundrum better
than its British counterpart. In Britain broadcasters wring their hands and
say 'Blacks are disadvantaged so we will provide special slots where they
can do their own thing and showcase their own culture'. This unthinking form
of apartheid assumes that black people cannot co-operate let alone compete
with whites but must be treated like babies. Often the results have been
programmes watched by a minority of a minority.
Americans, with their tradition of the melting pot philosophy, tend to say
'Bill Cosby? Who cares what colour he is? Is he talented? Give him a
series', and the series tops the ratings. Today BBC2 begins an acclaimed
American mini-series, Laurel Avenue, stripped across three nights and played
out in real time. It is about a lower middle class family which, as the
executive producer points out, just happens to be black. The appeal is in
the impact and honesty of the drama (9.30).
Earlier Alexei Sayle winds up his BBC1 series about driving skills, Drive
(8.50).
</TEXT>
