<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / Labour retreats on election pledge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour party yesterday issued its most unequivocal statement that it has
disavowed its 1992 election pledge to increase basic state pensions for all.
At a Fabian society conference Mr Donald Dewar, shadow social security
secretary, said that raising basic pensions for all was impracticable. 'The
problems can't be solved by simply raising the basic state pension,' he
said. 'The Labour party believes pension provision should reflect increasing
national wealth and make a significant contribution to security in
retirement. But we have to recognise the limitations.'
Labour party officials have privately acknowledged that the pledge to raise
basic pensions for all had limited flexibility on other spending pledges and
committed the party to unpopular tax rises.
However, Mr Dewar also made clear that Labour was not interested in
means-testing the basic state pension, saying it must continue to be
universal. He also called for direct statutory regulation of personal
pensions.
Meanwhile Mr Frank Field, the Labour MP who chairs the Commons social
security committee, unveiled at the same conference a plan for a National
Savings Personal Pensions Plan.
Investments in the plan would be linked to one or more index-tracking fund
and cover a range of bonds and equities. Its management could be contracted
out to the private sector and would have very low charges.
When pensions become payable, there will be an 'open market option' to
enable pensioners to purchase annuities from the most competitive life
insurance companies.
</TEXT>
