<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / London School of Economics and Political Science say student
loans should be privatised
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's student loans scheme should be privatised, with repayments
collected via National Insurance contributions, say a group of academics
from the London School of Economics and Political Science.
In a report they say that government spending per student has been reduced
by more than a third between 1974 and 1990, and 'the result has been an
erosion in quality'.
Student loans are organised by the Student Loans Company, an education
department quango, and repaid in fixed instalments.
The academics say asking for repayments via an extra percentage point of
income on National Insurance contributions would minimise the deterrent
effect.
Average repayment periods would be longer but low earners or part-time
workers would repay more than under the current scheme, which exempts all
those paid less than 85 per cent of average earnings from repayments.
</TEXT>
