<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / Oxbridge benefits from grant share-out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Oxford and Cambridge are among the greatest gainers from the reallocation of
government grants to universities for the academic year 1994-5.
Both received increases of 5.8 per cent compared with this year's total
funding. Only the London Business School and the Open University are ahead
of them.
Professor Graeme Davies, chief executive of the Higher Education Funding
Council for England, said both universities had benefited from a
reassessment of research funding.
They also avoided being penalised for over-expansion last year. Less
traditionally prestigious universities which also secured funding increases
of more than 5 per cent included Coventry, Plymouth, and Portsmouth, all of
which were polytechnics until two years ago.
The London School of Economics and Political Science, educator of numerous
world leaders, is one of nine universities limited to a below-inflation
increase of only 1 per cent. Bristol, another traditionally prestigious
university, is also among the nine.
Last year the LSE announced a plan to charge students an extra fee for
tuition, claiming this would be necessary to maintain academic standards.
This was eventually voted down by lecturers, but the move indicated that the
LSE was unhappy with its level of funding.
Some specialist institutions that do not have university status enjoyed
spectacular shifts in funding. Lackham College of Agriculture near
Chippenham secured the greatest rise in grant - 55.4 per cent.
The effect on intakes next year will vary widely between different
universities. Changes in overall funding will have less impact than the
target figure set by the funding council.
The University of East Anglia, despite an increase of 3.4 per cent in
funding, predicted it would have to cut intake by about 8 per cent compared
with last year.
It said the funding council had not taken into account the number of
four-year courses it offered, so it would be able to accommodate its cap on
total admissions only by cutting the number it introduced in the first year.
It said that other universities could be affected by the same problem.
Prof Davies predicted that the sharpest cuts, of around 10 per cent, would
be made by the former higher-education colleges, such as Derby and Luton,
which boosted their admissions while pre-paring bids for university status.
</TEXT>
