<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / BT looks abroad for video trials
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
British Telecommunications announced yesterday that its video-on-demand
trials will use technology developed by north American and French companies.
Two trials are planned for this year. The first, covering 70 BT employees in
Kesgrave near Ipswich, will be a technical trial. It will be followed later
this year by a commercial trial involving 2,500 residents in a place yet to
be decided.
The trials will pilot two technologies: the use of ADSL electronics to
upgrade copper wire to carry video pictures; and the more ambitious option
of extending fibre-optics into the home.
Northern Telecom, the Canadian telecoms manufacturer, has won the contract
for the ADSL equipment. Alcatel, the French supplier, will provide the fibre
technology.
Three US companies - Oracle, nCube and Apple Computer - will supply software
and hardware. Oracle will provide software and systems-integration services,
nCube will provide multimedia server hardware and Apple Computer will supply
'set top boxes' to decode the digital multimedia signals.
The technical trial will be limited to programming, using material supplied
by broadcasters including the BBC, Carlton Communications, London Weekend
Television and Granada. The commercial trial may extend to information
services.
On the basis of the experiments, BT will decide whether to proceed with a
heavy investment - about Pounds 15bn - to upgrade its network to provide
broadband services.
Until recently, BT insisted that the government's refusal to allow it to
provide entertainment services until at least 2001 made it uneconomic to
extend fibre down to the local network. But, with US phone companies
announcing ambitious network modernisation plans, senior BT executives are
anxious not to be left behind.
Participants in the initial trial will be able to call up more than 250
hours of programming through video remote-control devices. The material is
transmitted from a central database over the upgraded telephone network to
the television.
</TEXT>
