<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / Take-home pay gulf broadens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The gulf between the take-home pay of chief executives and that of other
employees has broadened markedly in the past 15 years according to figures
released today by a leading employment researcher, Richard Donkin writes.
Comparisons published by Incomes Data Services in its latest management pay
review also demonstrate that recent government figures recognising that the
tax burden had shifted conspicuously from high to low earners did not show
the full extent of the earnings gap that had developed.
While the take-home pay of employees on average earnings has grown fourfold
since 1978-79, chief executives' pay after deductions has increased on
average more than sixfold, according to the report. The differences in the
rate at which earnings have multiplied become apparent when comparing gross
earnings of both income groups. In the period from 1978-79 to 1994-95, the
average gross earnings of a chief executive rose by nearly six times from
Pounds 18,333 to the Pounds 106,168 that would be earned in the coming
financial year. The gross pay of those on average earnings increased by just
over four times from Pounds 4,826 to a projected Pounds 19,463 in the same
period.
Changes in the tax regime only served to compound the effect on
differentials, says the report.
IDS Management Pay Review. IDS, 193 St John Street, London EC1V 4LS. By
subscription.
</TEXT>
