<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / Three jailed after accepting bribes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Three businessmen who admitted accepting bribes to influence the awarding of
contracts for big engineering projects were jailed for between six months
and two years at Southwark Crown Court yesterday.
Mr Donald Richards, the former head of Donnar Services, a marketing and
personnel company, was imprisoned for two years and fined Pounds 30,000. Mr
Robert Wilcox and Mr Colin Read, both former employees of NEI Thompson
Kennicott, the engineering company, were jailed for one year and six months
respectively.
All three had admitted various charges of conspiracy to corrupt.
Mr Read and Mr Wilcox had passed confidential information about bids for
contracts to Mr Richards. He then passed it on to rival bidders, who were
able to win subcontracts from NEI. The bulk of the contracts involved work
on the Sizewell B and Drax power stations.
Judge Valerie Pearlman said: 'Each of you knowingly and willingly behaved in
the way you did for money, motivated solely by greed. Corruption does a
grave injury to the commerce of this country and . . . those who indulge in
it must expect to receive immediate sentences of imprisonment.'
