<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / Malaysia upsets the Ipswich roadshow: The trade ban has
dashed the hopes of many exporters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Spare a thought for the 26 members of the Ipswich and Suffolk Chamber of
Commerce who are visiting Malaysia. A week ago they packed their bags and
headed east, hopes high for handsome trade deals.
When they visited Malaysia last year they bagged more than MDollars 2m
(Pounds 500,000) worth of contracts with a promise of bigger things to come.
But the chamber reckoned without last week's Malaysian announcement banning
government contracts with British companies in retaliation for British media
allegations linking senior Malaysian officials, including Dr Mahathir
Mohamad, the prime minister, with under-the-counter payments by British
companies.
A British High Commission reception for the entrepreneurs of Ipswich and
Suffolk has been cancelled. Chamber members who spent several thousand
pounds on the trip are likely to find the business community in Malaysia
less than pleased to see them.
But while British business is busy calculating the many millions of pounds
worth of contracts likely to be lost through the Malaysian move, there is
growing concern on the other side of the fence as well.
A senior manager in one of Malaysia's biggest companies said: 'I don't think
the government really calculated the damage it was doing when it took its
action. Business goes two ways. I'm very worried about the consequences of
this.'
Malaysian business executives have raised concern that Britain might seek to
make the ban a European Union issue. By coincidence, Sir Leon Brittan, the
European Commissioner, was in Beijing this week warning the Chinese that any
attempt to punish British companies for the row over Hong Kong would be
viewed seriously by the EU as a whole.
There is also concern that the ban might be contrary to the spirit, if not
the letter, of Gatt. Mrs Rafidah Aziz, the Malaysian minister of industry
and trade, said the Malaysian move was limited to government contracts with
British companies and did not therefore contravene Gatt. However the
Malaysian government has wide-ranging influence over the private sector.
There is confusion among foreign companies that have joined consortia with
British and local companies to tender for government contracts. Many such
consortia are not simple to disband. This is the case with the Pounds 3.5bn
airport project outside Kuala Lumpur which was to have been undertaken by a
UK/Japanese consortium.
There are likely to be grumblings from local partners of British companies
who will now lose their share in millions of pounds worth of contracts.
Many of these companies are headed by influential Malay businessmen, some of
whom are prominent members of the United Malays National Organisation, the
dominant political party in the country.
Several Malaysian companies have been planning fundraising exercises in
Europe. The first stop for such roadshows is usually London. British fund
managers have given no indication that they are going to withdraw any of the
millions they have invested in the fast growing Malaysian market. But some
awkward questions might be addressed to visiting Malaysian business leaders.
There is also some confusion about what does and does not constitute a
British company. For example, Shell, the UK-Dutch group, operates refineries
and is involved, along with Petronas, the Malaysian state oil company, in
one of the world's biggest gasification projects.
Perhaps Shell will now be emphasising its 60 per cent Dutch ownership. Other
companies might find it more difficult to assert non-British credentials.
But the Ipswich and Suffolk Chamber of Commerce appears to be optimistic
about a change in policy: it told local reporters it planned to send another
mission to Malaysia next year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
