<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / Heseltine sets out economic manifesto
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, yesterday called for
radical new thinking on the roles of the government and the private sector
in promoting growth.
Delivering the annual Stockton lecture on the theme of obstacles to future
prosperity, Mr Heseltine set out what amounted to a personal manifesto on
the future of Britain.
In a wide-ranging speech, he repeatedly stressed the limits on the powers of
government, the crucial role of the private sector, and the constraints on
the use of taxation or borrowing to promote investment.
He was also critical of bureaucratic over-regulation in the European Union,
which he claimed had led to an 'over-protected, over-centralised community
suffering from 'Eurosclerosis'.
The speech will inevitably be seen as an attempt by Mr Heseltine to keep
open the option of a further bid for the Conservative party leadership if Mr
John Major, the prime minister, is forced to step down before the next
election.
Mr Heseltine's endorsement of fiscal conservatism, his stress on the role of
the private sector, and criticisms of the EU will appeal to rightwingers who
have recently begun to offer him support.
Many on the right would prefer to see Mr Heseltine in Downing Street than Mr
Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, who is regarded as too interventionist and
too sympathetic to the EU.
Mr Heseltine's friends have let it be known recently that he remains a
candidate for Number 10, in spite of his defeat in the 1990 leadership
election and the heart attack he suffered last year.
However, Mr Heseltine was careful to offer his support to Mr Major, who he
described as 'the first of the European leaders' to seek a solution to the
EUs structural problems.
His comments also amounted to a stinging rebuke to Baroness Thatcher, the
former prime minister, who is regarded by her supporters as an effective
critic of the EU.
Mr Heseltine said the world faced great opportunities as a result of the
collapse of communism, liberalisation of world trade, and the information
technology revolution.
But he said 'new techniques and thinking' were required to overcome
obstacles to growth.
</TEXT>
