<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / Minister warns unions of curb on pay rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A government minister told the Trades Union Conference yesterday that future
pay rises for the 5.8m public-sector workers would have to be funded from
efficiency savings and not increases in government funding.
Defending the government's three-year public-sector pay bill freeze Mr
Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to the Treasury, explained to delegates
at a TUC public services conference in London that there was 'no formal
limit on pay settlements' in the public sector. Mr Dorrell, the first Tory
minister in many years to address a TUC conference, received a cool
reception from delegates.
Mr Dorrell said there was a 'continuing role' for the existing five
pay-review bodies in the public services but he added that future pay awards
would have 'to take account of wider management considerations', such as the
spread of performance pay and local wage determination.
However the unions are likely to find it hard to convince workers to oppose
the government's public-sector wage policy. Nearly two in every five workers
are unaware that the government has any public-sector pay policy, a survey
commissioned by the TUC reported yesterday. Only 31 per cent knew there was
a 1.5 per cent pay limit last year and 20 per cent that the government had
introduced a pay-bill freeze.
A total of 85 per cent of the survey sample had not heard of any union
campaign against the government's public-pay policy.
The Post Office is continuing to face stiff resistance from the Treasury in
its efforts to win commercial freedom in its business activities. The
government is agreeing to lift existing financial restrictions that all its
investment programmes must be funded from its own profits.
But at yesterday's conference Mr Dorrell, in reply to Mr Alan Johnson,
leader of the UCW postal union, rejected a proposal on the use of public
money.
'I am not in favour of seeing the Post Office using taxpayer's money in the
form of public capital to compete openly with taxpayers in other
industries,' he said.
Mr Dorrell added: 'If we are being told that the Treasury should no longer
take an interest in the Post Office's use of public capital, then that is
not going to be the position.'
Mr Johnson said: 'This is very depressing.' If the Post Office could not
work with private companies it would mean European postal companies would
pick up business.
Observer, Page 19
</TEXT>
