<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / Builder for Channel link sought
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government may be able to avoid making any direct cash contribution to
the Pounds 2.7bn Channel tunnel rail link, Mr Roger Freeman, transport
minister said yesterday.
He was speaking at the launch of a competition to find a private-sector
consortium to build the 68-mile rail link between London's St Pancras
station and the Channel tunnel. It is expected to be the largest joint
public-private sector construction project this decade.
The size of the public contribution will depend on negotiations with the
private consortia that bid to build the line, but it is expected to consist
of:
The Pounds 800m assets owned by European Passenger Services, the company
which will run trains between London, Paris and Brussels. These comprise
Waterloo International station, the North Pole rail depot in north-west
London and the Eurostar rolling stock. The government will not transfer the
Pounds 1bn of debt incurred to acquire these assets.
The right to revenues from EPS's train services when these start this
summer.
The right to charge domestic train-operating companies a fee for running
trains over the rail link's tracks.
The intellectual property built up by Union Railway, the company which has
been developing the rail link for the past six years. No formal value has
been given to this.
The winning consortium is expected to be the one which bids for the smallest
amount of government contribution to the link. The government expects there
to be three or four serious bidders.
Companies have until April 25 to express an interest in the project but the
formal tendering process will begin in June and bids must be made by
December.
The winning consortium will be required to build a line capable of carrying
at least six trains an hour each way at speeds of up to 140 mph.
The government expects to introduce a bill authorising the project by the
end of the year with the aim of passing the legislation in 1996. The rail
link could then open in 2002.
In a new move the government said it would also pay 33 per cent of bid costs
 -up to a maximum of Pounds 1.5m - for each failed bidder.
</TEXT>
