<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / Procedure for challenging government in court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The House of Lords rulings over the procedure for challenging the government
in the UK courts could prove a greater blow to ministers than those on the
specific issue of part-time workers, some senior lawyers believe, writes
John Mason.
The rulings are likely to leave the government having to defend itself
against an increased number of legal actions brought by pressure groups and
others.
First, groups challenging issues of European law will now be able to bring
them through the judicial review procedure in the High Court. This would
prove both easier and quicker than having cases heard by the European Court
in Luxembourg.
Second, the legal position of pressure groups seeking to bring any kind of
actions before the UK courts has also been strengthened.
The result of both rulings could be the government having to defend its
policies more often and in the greater public spotlight offered by London
rather than Luxembourg.
The law lords overturned a Court of Appeal ruling that judicial review
proceedings in the High Court were not an appropriate forum for hearing
cases on European issues. In approving the use of High Court judicial
reviews, they have given pressure groups and others the opportunity to
bypass the long process of taking cases to the European Court.
Cases that are taken to the European Court may take four to six years to
resolve. If a judicial review application is expedited and approved, the
case can be before the High Court in a matter of days - as demonstrated by
the reviews over Maastricht and the challenge to the government's pit
closure programme.
The High Court could, however, still decide to refer the case to Europe
rather than proceed with a judicial review.
The law lords also strengthened the position of pressure groups by ruling
that the Equal Opportunities Commission had 'locus standi' in this case - in
effect it was suitably qualified to act on behalf of part-time workers. This
principle has often been disputed.
</TEXT>
<XX>
