FT  04 MAR 94 / India's exports surge 21%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SHIRAZ SIDHVA
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
India's exports surged 21.41 per cent to Dollars 17.8bn (Pounds 9.8bn) in
the 10 months from April 1993 to January this year. Preliminary figures
yesterday showed that while exports are continuing to grow strongly, imports
in the period increased only 0.68 per cent to Dollars 18.38bn against last
year's Dollars 18.26bn. The trade deficit fell from Dollars 3.6bn in the 10
months to Dollars 581.68m.
Main commodities that have led to the growth in exports are gems and
jewellery (18 per cent); ready-made garments (12.3 per cent); engineering
goods (9 per cent); textiles (6.8 per cent), and leather goods (3.9 per
cent). Imports continued to be dominated by petroleum and crude oil.
The Asian Development Bank yesterday approved a Dollars 600,000 grant for
emergency rehabilitation management in Maharashtra, where 10,000 people were
killed in an earthquake last September.
