<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / Venezuelan judge orders 83 arrests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOSEPH MANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CARACAS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A Venezuelan judge has issued 83 warrants against some of the country's most
prominent businessmen in connection with the collapse of Venezuela's second
largest bank, Banco Latino, in January.
Criminal Court Judge Diamora Ramirez de Simancas ordered the arrests of two
ex-presidents of Banco Latino, members of the board of directors and deputy
directors, bank officers, and Mr Roger Urbina, the superintendent of banks,
who was charged with concealment.
Also charged was Mr Ricardo Cisneros, one of the wealthiest men in Latin
America, whose family owns large industrial and commercial holdings in
Venezuela and the US. Mr Cisneros was formerly a member of Latino's board,
and the Cisneros group of companies reported that it owned 3.5 per cent of
the bank's stock.
Mr Cisneros and his brother, Gustavo, own the Organizacion Diego Cisneros in
Venezuela as well as the Spalding, Evenflo and Pueblo Xtra supermarkets in
the US. Mr Gustavo Cisneros has denied wrongdoing by him, his brother or his
family companies in the Latino affair.
The Cisneroses formerly owned Paternoster Square in London and the Galerias
Preciados chain in Spain.
Most of those involved are believed to have left the country, even though
the authorities had issued international travel bans against members of
Latino's board in January. The judge asked the government to initiate
extradition proceedings against any of those charged who are found overseas.
The warrants covered charges that included illegal appropriation, fraud, and
falsification of financial statements.
Arrest warrants were issued against two ex-presidents of Latino, Messrs
Gustavo Gomez Lopez and Giacomo Leon, and a list of others that reads like a
Who's Who of Venezuelan businessmen and investors.
It is not clear how far the current legal actions will proceed.
</TEXT>
