<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / Secret service 'out of control'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A parliamentary report has criticised Mr Nicola Mancino, Italy's interior
minister, for failing to exercise proper control of the domestic
intelligence services, writes Robert Graham from Rome. The report, released
yesterday, followed the discovery of large scale misuse of the
organisations' funds and suspicions that secret servicemen had been involved
in planting of last summer's bombs in Florence, Milan and Rome. The report
says Mr Mancino lacked 'effective control' and his knowledge of the
activities of the domestic intelligence (Sisde) was 'episodic'. More often
than not, he was informed only after operations had been concluded. However,
the minister's supervisory role had been handicapped by the 1977 laws
setting up the Sisde, which gave its officials virtual autonomy.
