Tom Burns from Madrid. The early morning cut surprised analysts, but
reaction was positive. Bond yields which had risen to above 9.6 per cent
fell to 8.8 per cent, the 3-month Mibor came down from 8.7 per cent to 8.3
per cent, Ibex-35, the index of the Madrid market's most traded equities,
rose 2.4 per cent and the peseta held steady. Meanwhile, figures released
yesterday revealed that GDP was down 0.3 per cent in the fourth quarter of
1993 against a year earlier, but up by 0.1 per cent on the third quarter of
1993.
