<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / France calls for European rapid intervention force
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Francois Leotard, the French defence minister, yesterday suggested
setting up multinational European rapid intervention forces, a project far
more ambitious than the Franco-German-Belgian Eurocorps now being created,
Reuter reports from Paris. Mr Leotard, in a speech to a symposium on
European defence, called for a summit of the nine-member Western European
Union (WEU), the designated security arm of the European Union. 'Such a
meeting could allow the Europeans, for example, to create European
intervention forces, commanded by a European general staff and which would
be both multinational and have integrated (air, land and sea) forces,' Mr
Leotard said. The Eurocorps, seen as the future land-based defence force of
the WEU, will become operational later this year, with one French and one
German division plus a Belgian brigade. But the Strasbourg-based Eurocorps
will have no air or naval forces of its own and Mr Leotard linked his new
plan to an existing one for the creation of an air and naval force made up
of French, Spanish and Italian units. Mr Leotard said he was not seeking to
rival Nato, of which France remains a member but whose integrated military
command it left in 1966 because of US dominance.
</TEXT>
