<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / French students protest against plan to lower young people's
pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Some 10,000 French students marched through Paris yesterday in protest
against a law allowing employers to pay young workers less than the minimum
wage as trade union leaders pressed the prime minister, Mr Edouard Balladur,
for concessions, Reuter reports from Paris.
The communist-led CGT union walked out of round-table talks with Mr Balladur
after three hours when the conservative prime minister refused to withdraw
the controversial law, but non-communist unions continued to negotiate in
the hope of winning key changes.
The CGT general secretary, Mr Louis Viannet, said: 'The prime minister made
a number of proposals which are no more than cosmetic changes. In these
conditions the CGT cannot condone the talks.'
Mr Viannet later joined the front rank of the protest march, along with
student union leaders, near Mr Balladur's Paris office.
The law, disapproved of by most French voters according to an opinion poll,
allows young people under 26 on 'training contracts' to be paid between 30
and 80 per cent of the minimum wage, known as the SMIC, even if they have
university diplomas.
The talks with unions and employers to discuss ways of combating record 12.2
per cent unemployment were arranged before controversy erupted last week
over what unions and left-wing political parties have dubbed the
'Youth-SMIC'.
'This protest is just a foretaste,' student leader Philippe Campinchi said.
'The aim is to organise a national demonstration in the coming days to
demand the scrapping of this law.'
Mr Marc Blondel, leader of the moderate Force Ouvriere union, who stayed in
the talks, said Mr Balladur had offered amendments to limit the application
of the contracts, make them experimental and ensure that young people were
given real training.
'There can be no question of the unions, and particularly Force Ouvriere,
accepting this notion of a Youth-SMIC,' he said.
Mr Viannet said the measure undermined the minimum wage - which currently
stands at FFr5,886 (Pounds 674) a month for a 39-hour week.
Mr Balladur has denied the measure discriminates against young workers or
subverts the minimum wage.
With his credibility at stake after several recent policy reverses, the
prime minister has vowed he will not back down.
</TEXT>
