<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / PM holds out hope of more troops for Bosnia: United Nations
calls for near doubling of ground forces to protect fragile ceasefires
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain yesterday held out the possibility that it might send more troops to
Bosnia after the United Nations called on the international community to
almost double its forces in the former Yugoslav province.
But amid signs of a cabinet split and fears of a backlash on the
Conservative backbenches, it rejected a request from General Sir Michael
Rose, the UN commander in Bosnia, for immediate reinforcement of Britain's
2,500 troops.
Responding to the latest UN plea for an extra 10,650 soldiers to join the
13,000 already in Bosnia, Mr John Major, the prime minister, said British
help would be proportionate to and contingent on increased participation in
the peace effort.
Mr Yasushi Akashi, the UN special envoy for the former Yugoslavia, warned
that without the extra troops fragile ceasefires could collapse. Gen Rose
said his troops were operating 'on a wing and a prayer'.
The US is also coming under pressure to send ground troops to Bosnia.
General Jean Cot, head of the UN's peacekeeping forces in the former
Yugoslavia, said it was a 'strange and not very courageous idea' that the US
would consider sending troops only after a peace settlement was secured.
After discussion at the weekly cabinet meeting, Mr Major told British MPs:
'If a request is made to the UK, we would of course consider providing more
forces proportionately as part of a wider international effort.'
His comment reflected a view among some leading ministers that if the
situation in Bosnia continues to improve Britain would find it hard to
resist pressure for additional forces. Ministers said the new position in
Sarajevo has opened up the prospect of a new phase in the civil war in which
the UN would be required to police a number of regional settlements.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the defence secretary, is also under pressure from the
army chiefs of staff to meet Gen Rose's request for more troops. It is
understood that in spite of recent cuts in army numbers, a battalion of
about 900 soldiers could be sent to Bosnia at short notice.
But the latest request also opened up the prospect of a cabinet struggle
with those ministers who remain opposed to further British commitments to
Bosnia.
Gen Rose has told Mr Rifkind that he needs more British troops with
experience of Northern Ireland. But some senior ministers - said to include
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Michael Heseltine, trade secretary
 -have opposed greater British involvement on the ground.
During yesterday's discussions Mr Rifkind held back from a formal suggestion
of British reinforcement. Mr Major fears that a swathe of rightwing Tory MPs
might rebel if Britain increases its commitment. Mr Nicholas Budgen, a Tory
back bench opponent of further involvement, claimed growing support for his
view that the government risked a 'British Vietnam' in Bosnia.
The UN plea for more troops came amid talks between Bosnian Croats and
Moslems and Croat officials. They are due to meet in Vienna today for talks
on a federation for one part of Bosnia that will have an arrangement with
Croatia.
In an attempt to persuade Bosnia's Serbs to support these negotiations, Mr
Haris Silajdzic, the Bosnian prime minister, met Russian foreign ministry
officials.
</TEXT>
