<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 94 / S Times sends trade ban letter to Malaysia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Andrew Neil, editor of The Sunday Times, which carried an article said to
have provoked the Malaysian government into curbing trade with British
companies, has sent a message to Kuala Lumpur that could help thaw
relations.
Mr Neil has sent the Malaysian government a copy of a letter signed by him,
which appears in today's Times, stating that his newspaper has 'no vendetta
against Malaysia or its prime minister', Dr Mahathir Mohamad.
Meanwhile, Baroness Chalker, minister for overseas development, confirmed
that she had opposed government funding for the Pergau Dam project.
She denied, however, that Britain's aid-and-trade policy was a breeding
ground for financial corruption as alleged in a report by Professor John
Toye, an adviser to the Overseas Development Agency, which was circulated to
the Commons foreign affairs committee. Her evidence before the committee
came as Lord Younger, former defence secretary, said he alone had taken the
decision to link an offer of aid to arms sales.
Malaysia's deputy prime minister, Mr Anwar Ibrahim, was reported earlier
this week as saying that the trade ban would not be lifted until The Sunday
Times apologised for alleging that Dr Mahathir took a bribe.
Mr Neil states in his letter: 'I regret . . . if subsequent misreporting of
a Sunday Times story has led the Malaysian prime minister to believe he has
been accused by us of a charge we did not make.'
He adds: 'In the light of this clarification, I hope he will conclude that
there are no grounds for a ban on British companies doing business with his
government.'
A copy of the letter has been sent to the Malaysian High Commissioner in
London with a request that it be immediately dispatched to his government in
Kuala Lumpur.
Sources close to the Malaysian government described the letter as a 'step in
the right direction', which while not enough to end the trade ban might help
restore relations.
They suggested the letter may not be unconnected with Mr Rupert Murdoch's
media ambitions in Malaysia. Mr Murdoch's News International owns the Sunday
Times.
Aid policy 'bred corruption'; Malaysia upsets Ipswich roadshow; Scale of
Pergau cost queried, Page 7
