<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow sharply reverses early
plunge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
After plummeting more than 50 points at the opening following heavy losses
in overseas stocks and US bonds, share prices rallied impressively yesterday
to end firmly in positive territory, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 22.51 at 3,831.74,
which represented a 76-point swing from its low of the day of 3,755.76. The
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 moved in similar fashion to end a
net 0.37 ahead at 464.81. The American SE composite, however, remained weak,
finishing 3.64 down at 466.32, while the Nasdaq composite ended 5.17 lower
at 783.47.
NYSE volume was heavy at 361m shares, while declines still outnumbered rises
at the close by 1,424 to 772.
Heavy overnight selling on foreign equity and bond markets, and early
declines in US bond prices in New York, set the stage for a sharply downbeat
opening to equity trading.
Within minutes the Dow was showing a double-digit loss, and it was not long
before the average had posted a 50-point decline, which triggered the NYSE's
'circuit breakers', which limit program trading.
The circuit breakers, however, and a sharp rebound in US bond prices (the
30-year bond recovered from a one-point decline to end slightly higher),
stemmed the tide of selling. By midday, stocks were rallying, aided by the
news that the US government will not immediately take punitive action
against the Japanese for failing to open up their markets to US goods and
services.
With demand for cyclical issues (many of them components of the Dow) surging
during the afternoon, the market eventually moved back into the black. Yet,
in spite of the Dow's rebound, the wider market remained weak, and
investors' mood sombre.
Bond and stock prices in the US and Europe have been falling because of
fears that signs of resurgent inflation in the US will prompt the Federal
Reserve to put up interest rates again. Yesterday's report from the Commerce
Department that wages and salaries rose by 1 per cent in January - double
the growth in the previous month - only fuelled investors' fears about
inflation.
Among individual sectors, financial stocks again took a beating because of
concern about rising interest rates. Bankers Trust was hardest hit, falling
Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 78 3/8 after the New York bank was forced to issue
a statement denying rumours that it had incurred huge losses on its
derivatives trading. JP Morgan, down Dollars 1 at Dollars 66 1/2 , was
another to suffer from speculation about trading losses.
Elsewhere in the sector, Citicorp slipped Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 39 1/2 and
Nationsbank Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 47 7/8 .
Car manufacturers led the market's recovery, Ford Motor rising Dollars 1 7/8
to Dollars 64 1/8 , General Motors Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 60 1/2 and
Chrysler Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 57 3/8 .
Other cyclicals on the rise included Alcoa, up Dollars 2 at Dollars 76 1/2 ,
Caterpillar, Dollars 3 higher at Dollars 112, General Electric, Dollars 1
ahead at Dollars 105 7/8 , and Union Carbide, Dollars  1/2 firmer at Dollars
24 1/2 .
Canada
Toronto stocks shook off much of their earlier rate-driven weakness in
afternoon action, but failed to match New York's resurgence and ended still
easier on the day.
The TSE-300 composite index closed 28.2 down at 4,362.2 after tumbling
almost 57 points early in the session. Falls finally led rises by 513 to 249
after volume of 63.8m shares.
Eleven of the 14 stock groups declined, led by the golds sector, off 2.50
per cent. However, the Comex gold bullion price finished only USDollars 0.50
easier at USDollars 378.90 after trading as low as USDollars 374.00 per
ounce.
