<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 94 / International Company News: Chief quits French financial
group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jean-Louis Petriat, one of France's most prominent businessmen, yesterday
resigned as chairman and chief executive of Garantie Mutuelle des
Fonctionnaires (GMF), the ailing financial services group.
The departure of Mr Petriat, 59, marks the latest instalment in the troubled
recent history of GMF, a powerful force in the French insurance market, but
one which has faced heavy losses from an unsuccessful property venture in
the Netherlands Antilles, and from its travel insurance business.
The losses from these ventures forced GMF into capital-raising moves
designed to stabilise finances. Last year, it had to put up for sale its
controlling interest in FNAC, the largest chain of music and book stores in
France.
The FNAC sale, however, was clouded by controversy when the French stock
market authorities mounted an official investigation into a bid from Altus
Finance and Compagnie Immobiliere Phenix, after complaints from minority
shareholders. Altus and Phenix were eventually forced to raise the value of
their offer.
Mr Petriat, a flamboyant figure known for his penchant for bow-ties, has
been chairman of GMF since 1987. He has come under the spotlight in recent
years as the chief opponent of the Sunday trading campaign mounted by
Virgin, the UK-based retail group and FNAC's strongest competitor in France.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Garantie Mutuelle des Fonctionnaires et Employes d'Etat
    des Services Publiques.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6321 Accident and Health Insurance.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
