FT  03 MAR 94 / International Company News: Saga Petroleum increases payout
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Saga Petroleum, Norway's biggest independent oil company, has reported a
steep rise in pre-tax profits for 1993 and is increasing its dividend from
NKr1.75 a share to NKr2.
Group operating revenues advanced to NKr5.66bn (Dollars 764m) for 1993
compared with NKr4.92bn for the previous year after an increase in operating
costs to NKr3.97bn from NKr3.67bn. Pre-tax profits for the year were NKr1bn,
against NKr802m.
The charge for net financial items was NKr688m in 1993, up from NKr449m in
1992. Included in last year's charge is a net unrealised currency loss of
NKr451m on dollar-denominated debt.
Last year total crude oil production surged by 22 per cent to 35.9m barrels
as daily crude oil production rose to 98,400 barrels from 80,700 barrels,
helped mainly by the first full year of output from the Snorre field.
Crude oil sales rose by 4.5m barrels to 31m in 1993 as gas sales fell to
465m cubic metres from 485m. Tariff revenue from pipeline systems rose to
NKr503m from NKr450m.
At the end of 1993, Saga's remaining proved and probable oil and gas
reserves totalled 147.4m tonnes of oil equivalent.
