<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 94 / Biggest monthly rise in house prices since 1988 reported
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Further evidence of the continuing recovery in the UK housing market emerged
yesterday as Halifax, Britain's biggest mortgage lender, confirmed that
house prices rose 2.2 per cent in February, the biggest monthly gain since
September 1988.
Figures produced by the Inland Revenue show that the number of homes sold
has also risen sharply.
According to Halifax the average price of homes has risen 3.8 per cent in
the past 12 months to Pounds 62,498. The latest price rise follows two
months of small price falls. The society said this confirmed that the slow
recovery which started in the housing market last year was continuing.
Inland Revenue conveyancing records show that the 113,000 house purchases
completed in England and Wales in January were more than a third higher than
the figure in January last year.
Conveyancing completions have exceeded 100,000 in all of the last seven
months compared to just once in the previous seven. Even so sales last year
rose only 5.1 per cent to 1.19m.
This compared with a low of 1.13m in 1992. The 1993 figure was still the
second lowest annual result since transactions peaked at 2.14m in 1988.
Halifax said that if the recent trend continued transactions could rise by
between 10 per cent and 15 per cent this year, which would be the highest
level since 1990.
The society expects prices to rise at a slower rate and is forecasting an
average increase of 5 per cent this year.
It warned purchasers and sellers not to read too much into one month's
figures, saying that the rate of annual price increase was likely to fall in
the next two months 'because of the large monthly rise which occured last
March and April'.
As a result the society 'would expect to see much smaller rises in coming
months'.
According to the society the average price of a new house rose 0.4 per cent
in February and 1.7 per cent over 12 months to Pounds 67,523.
Halifax's latest figures conflict with a report on Tuesday by Nationwide,
the country's second largest building society, which said that UK house
prices on average had fallen by 0.6 per cent in February compared with
January.
It is the third month running that the societies' figures have differed.
Nationwide in January and December reported monthly increases of 0.4 per
cent and 0.8 per cent respectively while Halifax reported falls of 0.4 per
cent and 0.6 per cent.
The societies are in closer agreement on the annual rate of increase, with
Nationwide reporting 3.2 per cent and Halifax 3.8 per cent.
</TEXT>
