<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 94 / Crackdown urged on fraudulent links
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies may be required to disclose details of all parties related to them
by transactions, under tough proposals designed to crack down on fraud.
Under Fred 8, the draft directive from the Accounting Standards Board,
related parties will include individuals or companies connected with,
influenced by or controlled by the company, its pension funds, its directors
and managers and their immediate families.
Fred 8 will make it more difficult to conceal many frauds associated with
recently-collapsed companies.
Mr David Tweedie, chairman of the board, said: 'This is a fraud-prevention
standard. We are asking companies to tell us what they would rather we did
not know.'
The discussion document calls for disclosure of all material related-party
transactions, including the name of the controlling party, any ultimate
controlling party, the amounts involved and any other information necessary
to understand the financial statements.
It requires disclosure of any transactions involving a material difference
between the fair value of an asset, liability or service and the transacted
amount. This would disclose practices such as the transfer of assets below
real value, and movements of money to and from the company.
The standard relies on auditors to insist on disclosure. The Auditing
Practices Board is developing guidelines on the subject.
Mr Tweedie said: 'If the auditors don't do their job, we are sunk.'
Fred 8 significantly extends the existing requirements under company law to
disclose related-party transactions, which need only be shown in accounts if
they are judged by the directors to be outside the normal course of business
activities.
The board's new provisions include children of directors regardless of their
age, and managers as well as board members.
Comments on the standard are due by June 15.
Fred 8. Related-party disclosures. ASB Publications, PO Box 939, Central
Milton Keynes, MK9 2HT. Pounds 5.
</TEXT>
<XX>
