<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 94 / Westminster auditor seizes papers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Magill, Westminster city council's district auditor, yesterday
impounded documents in the council's offices and said he is considering a
further investigation into the council's alleged 'gerrymandering' policy.
The documents were identified by Mr Magill and four of his assistants who
visited Westminster city hall yesterday morning. They will be held in 'joint
custody' by the council's acting managing director, Mr Bill Roots, and Mr
Magill at least until mid-October.
In January Mr Magill published provisional findings that six Conservative
councillors - one of whom has since committed suicide - and four council
officers should be surcharged Pounds 21.5m. He said they had manipulated the
council's housing policy so that council house sales were concentrated in
eight politically marginal wards.
Touche Ross, in which Mr Magill is a partner, said his visit to city hall
was not directly connected to the designated sales policy. It said: 'The
auditor and the council have received a number of questions on the 'Building
Stable Communities' policy of which designated sales are alleged to be a
part.' The documents held in custody are 'relevant to this matter'.
Mr Magill's priority is to resolve the designated sales inquiry before he
makes any further investigation.
He also announced that the nine people named in his January report will have
until April 8 to request an oral hearing on the allegations. This would then
take place in mid-October.
The 'Building Stable Communities' programme was launched by the council's
former leader, Dame Shirley Porter, in 1986. Its official aim is to prevent
the long-term migration of residents from Westminster and includes 'quality
of life' initiatives to improve the local environment and bans on office
developments in residential areas.
The council defended the policy by pointing to the 1991 census which showed
a rise in the borough's population over the previous 10 years. It had
previously decreased every census since 1911.
Mr Neale Coleman, co-ordinator of the objectors to Westminster's policy,
described yesterday's events as an 'anti-shredding manoeuvre'.
He said: 'If Mr Magill's final view is anything remotely approximate to his
provisional view then he plainly will have to investigate all the other
matters.'
</TEXT>
