<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 94 / Option of extra Bosnian troops 'not closed off'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Signs of a softening of government attitudes towards sending additional
British troops to Bosnia emerged at Westminster last night amid reports of a
looming clash on the issue between ministers and defence chiefs.
As officials sought to play down differences, saying service chiefs and
ministers were 'four-square in step', senior ministerial sources said the
option of sending extra troops had not been closed off.
Last month's request from General Sir Michael Rose, the British UN commander
based in Sarajevo, for an immediate addition of 3,000 troops had been seen
as premature, the sources said. Britain was unlikely to send more ground
troops if no other country did.
In public comments to date, ministers have tended to adopt the harder line
that if extra troops are needed they should come from countries which do not
already have forces on the ground.
As recently as yesterday, writing in London's Evening Standard newspaper, Mr
Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, said: 'The plan for opening Tuzla to
relief supplies should be carried out. Mostar, Vitez and the Maglaj pocket
need relief. This means redeploying the UN force and may need extra men.
Britain, France, Spain, Holland, Canada, Malaysia and many other countries
are doing their bit. The extra should come from elsewhere.'
Mr Hurd emphasised that the 2,500 British troops escorting convoys in the
region were 'a bigger contribution than any except the French'.
Contacted last night, Sir Nicholas Bonsor, chairman of the defence select
committee who is due to meet Gen Rose in Split next week, said he thought
there was a row between ministers and defence chiefs.
The chiefs were saying Britain should 'send what we can', while the
government's position was that 'others should do their bit'.
Sir Nicholas said it was his understanding that a request had been made to
the UN for an additional 7,000 troops. He 'absolutely' backed the
government's stance that Britain must not be drawn into the conflict 'inch
by inch'.
</TEXT>
