<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 94 / BCCI liquidators hit by file ban
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The liquidators to the collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce International
have been forbidden by a British Virgin Islands judge from using information
gained from examining banking files in the country last year.
The Honourable Mr Justice Ephraim Georges made the order last month against
four liquidators to the bank and Mr Michael Holden, the inspector of banks
and trust companies for British Virgin Islands.
It follows Mr Holden's decision late last year to grant liquidators from
Touche Ross, the accountancy firm, access to records about companies they
believed were connected to Sheikh Khalid bin Mahfouz. The liquidators are
suing National Commercial Bank of Saudi Arabia and Sheikh Khalid, its former
chief operating officer.
The records related to Connaught Place Investments, a company registered in
the British Virgin Islands which is believed to own residential property in
London.
