<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 94 / PIA warns over non-membership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Firms which refused to join the personal investment authority, the new
regulator for retail financial services, could find themselves effectively
under its regime anyway, Mr Joe Palmer, the authority's chairman, said
yesterday.
The statutory right to choose to be regulated directly by the Securities and
Investments Board, the City's chief watchdog, would survive but, he said,
SIB would be effective in deterring those who wanted to take that route.
SIB was 'quite likely' to tell those who wanted to come directly under its
control that it would apply the PIA rulebook and the PIA compensation scheme
arrangements.
Mr Palmer told the inquiry by the cross-party treasury committee of MPs into
financial regulation that such firms would then find themselves 'under our
framework of regulation without any say at all in how it was to be handled'.
In the 10 days since the PIA prospectus was published there have been a few
indications of support from within the life insurance industry. Many large
firms have continued to voice concern, however, while stopping short of
declaring that they would not sign up to the new regulator.
It is essential for the PIA's credibility as a regulator that it attracts
enough backing from life companies, banks, independent financial advisers
and others in the financial services sector.
Mr Palmer said: 'We need the willing support of at least the majority of the
industry we seek to regulate.'
But he and Ms Colette Bowe, PIA chief executive, faced scepticism from the
MPs about how effective the authority could be in checking standards across
its potential membership of 6,000 firms and individuals particularly since
in the case of the large life insurers and banks it would be dependent on
senior management for the control of individual sales agents.
</TEXT>
