<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 94 / Port admits unfair sackings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Port of Sheerness conceded yesterday that it had unfairly dismissed 247 of
its dock workers nearly a year ago, when they refused to accept new terms
and conditions of employment, including wage cuts of up to 60 per cent.
The former dockers have been offered cash compensation that could amount to
about Pounds 10,000 each but they are not expected to secure reinstatement
in their old jobs as they had wanted.
The dramatic climbdown by the employers came unexpectedly on the third day
of an industrial tribunal hearing into the case of the dismissed workers.
The dispute at Sheerness erupted after the privatisation of the port in
1991.
The workers alleged that they were told by the new company that they would
be made redundant if they rejected sweeping cuts in their pay and benefits.
When they started a work to rule they were dismissed, although with
redundancy. Their jobs have since been taken by others on the new terms and
conditions of employment. Mr Keith Watson, an official of the TGWU general
union at Tilbury, said yesterday: 'It is a marvellous victory for our
members.
'It shows workers can resist successfully the imposition of new contracts of
employment on them.'
He added: 'Employers everywhere are paying less and less attention to their
legal obligations to their workers. This case should give at least some
heart to those who want to resist employers ignoring the law.'
The tribunal will reconvene this afternoon. It is expected that a settlement
between the port and the dockers will be announced then.
</TEXT>
