<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAR 94 / Clarke turns on Labour tax critics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, yesterday countered a renewed onslaught
on his November Budget by accusing Labour of 'spreading myths' about the
effects of tax increases.
Mr Clarke mounted a vigorous defence of the government's taxation record, in
line with the Conservatives' determination to meet Labour criticism head on
in the campaigns for the forthcoming local and European election and Commons
by-elections.
His comments followed claims by Ms Harriet Harman, shadow chief secretary to
the Treasury, that the tax on insurance premiums announced in the Budget
amounted to a breach of the government's pledge not to extend the scope of
value added tax. 'The people of Britain will be hit by a triple whammy of
rising crime, rising insurance premiums and now a tax on their insurance
premiums,' she said.
